The XRD method is used to determine if a material is crystalline or amorphous. It will specify how cementation materials will be quantified. The atomic arrangement, crystallite size, and defects of crystalline materials may all be investigated via XRD analysis. An X-ray source of Cu Ka radiation (11/4 1.5406 Aͦͦ) is used for the XRD examination. It will use the Brag Brentano approach to evaluate and identify unknown crystalline substances [168, 169]. Because each solid substance has its own X-ray diffraction pattern, this approach may be used to determine the phases and components present. The XRD approach involves concentrating an X-ray beam at an initial angle of 2θ on the biopolymer membrane or film and then reading the intensity of the diffracted ray using specialized detectors. Following the reading, the incident ray's angle 2θ is changed for a fresh reading up to a final 2θ value Bragg's law governs the diffracted beam by crystalline phases (Eq. 1)1λ=2dsinθ\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
